────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
CORE PHILOSOPHY (MANDATORY)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Assume the reader is:
- New to the language OR
- Returning to the code after a long time

Write comments so that:
- A junior developer can follow the flow
- A senior developer can skim and trust the structure
- The intent of every non-trivial block is clear

Comments should explain:
- WHY something exists
- WHAT a block is responsible for
- WHEN something is executed
- HOW pieces fit together

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
COMMENT STYLE RULES (MANDATORY)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Use DIFFERENT comment styles for hierarchy.


LEVEL 1 — Major Sections
Use ONLY for true major boundaries
(e.g., file start, major subsystems).

- Spacing Rules:
Two (2) blank lines BEFORE the section header.
One (1) blank line AFTER the section header line.

- Syntax Rules:
The header uses the standard single comment char (e.g., #).
The details/description immediately following the header MUST use double comment chars (e.g., ## in Zsh/Python, // in C/JS/Go).

<comment> Section Title
<comment> ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

- Example:
'''
# Completion System
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
'''



- EDITORIAL / NARRATIVE SECTIONS (PREFERRED FOR FLOW)
Use this style for:
- CLI logic
- Entry points
- Execution flow
- User-facing control paths

<comment> ── section name ───────────────────────────────────────────────

Example:
'''
# ── cli / command-line interface ─────────────────────────────────────
'''


LEVEL 2 — Subsections
Introduce logical groupings inside a major section:

<comment> ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
<comment> Subsection Title


LEVEL 3 — Minor / Helper Sections
Use subtle inline styles:

<comment> · helper utilities
or
<comment> :: key bindings

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
INFORMATIONAL COMMENT RULES (VERY IMPORTANT)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

You MUST add explanatory comments throughout the code.

Specifically:
- Explain what each function does in plain language.
- Explain what each parameter represents.
- Explain return values if non-obvious.
- Explain complex expressions or chained calls.
- Explain conditionals (what case they are handling).
- Explain loops (what is being iterated and why).
- Explain data structures (what they contain and how they are used).

Use comments like:
- "This function is responsible for…"
- "At this point in execution…"
- "We use X here because…"
- "This block handles the case where…"

DO NOT:
- Repeat the code verbatim in comments
- State obvious syntax facts (e.g., “this is a for loop”)
- Over-comment trivial one-liners

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Semantic / Intent Markers (MANDATORY WHEN APPLICABLE)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Use strong markers for intent:

<comment> !!! CRITICAL: explanation
<comment> ---- TEMP: explanation
<comment> ---- SAFE: explanation
<comment> ---- NOTE: explanation

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Folding (IDE-friendly, if applicable)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

<comment>#region Section Name
...
<comment>#endregion

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FORMATTING & ALIGNMENT RULES (MANDATORY)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

- Align assignment operators (`=`, `:=`, `=>`) vertically within logical blocks.
- Align dictionary / object / map colons (`:`) vertically.
- Align trailing commas (`,`) in multi-line structures where applicable.
- Align keyword arguments when it improves readability.
- Maintain consistent indentation per language conventions.
- NEVER sacrifice correctness for alignment or modify spaces inside the strings or somewhere that will break the code functioning.

- Examples:
'''
Before:
a=1
long_variable=2
x   =3

After:
a             = 1
long_variable = 2
x             = 3
'''

'''
Before:
{
  "a":1,
  "long_key":2,
  "x":3
}

After:
{
  "a"        : 1,
  "long_key" : 2,
  "x"        : 3
}
'''

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
GENERAL STYLE RULES
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

- Balance aesthetics with clarity.
- Avoid excessive decoration.
- Emojis ONLY if semantically meaningful.
- Prefer readable structure over visual noise.
- Comments should explain intent, not mechanics.
- Maintain a calm, professional, terminal-native tone.

Language Awareness:
- Use the correct comment syntax for the language.
- Do not introduce comment styles that break syntax.

